    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Timing of a Pardon</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Steven Slawson says way to avoid travesty of justice such as Pres Clinton's pardon of Marc Rich, presidents should be permitted to use pardon only during first three and half years of their term</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pardons on the Sly'' (editorial, Jan. 25):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pardons on the Sly'' (editorial, Jan. 25):</p>
        <p>I share your outrage over President Bill Clinton's pardons (particularly that of Marc Rich, the fugitive commodities trader). I propose that to avoid such a travesty of justice in the future, each president be permitted to use the pardon only during the first three and a half years of his term. I wonder if Mr. Clinton would have acted in the same manner if he (and Al Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton) had had to live with this during the elections.</p>
        <p>STEVEN SLAWSON  Warren, N.J., Jan. 25, 2001</p>
      </block>
